Camp North End is a Charlotte must. The campus bursts with urban art, color drenched murals, installations, and sculptures around every turn. Set against a beautifully preserved industrial vibe of warehouses, steel, and string lights. Wide-open courtyards and walkways make it perfect for lingering. There’s a strong mix of restaurants (from coffee and cocktails to pizza, tacos, and sweet treats), independent shops and galleries, and plenty of creative offices that keep the place buzzing. And don’t miss the famous Tipsy Pickleball, courts, drinks, and good vibes all in one spot.

reviews_data.review_text:
I have been here a couple of times as there's a coworking space that I use. This is an interesting space that was originally a Model T factory back in the 1920s and then was used by the US Army to assemble missiles during the Cold War. The space still feels very industrial but it's been updated and adapted into offices, meeting spaces, bars and hangouts.

All sorts of open air play spaces, farmers markets, live music and the Keswick food stall / pop-up area. Some of the parking is free, some is paid. I used the spaces north of the space along Graham for free.
